nodes.title: 4MOOF NOTES
widgets_values:
Shout-outs and thanks to StabilityAI team for building this great tech and making it open source. Also thanks to Scott Detweiler, Amli, ComfyAnonymous, and Olivio Sarikas for your tech and tutorials. A lot of my ideas and insights come from playing with an experimenting with these tools, but I wouldn't even know they exist and how to use them without the tutorials and readme(s) for help. 

4MOOF is the third public iteration of my SMOOSH workflow to create WILD UNPREDICTABLE AI ART with SDXL and ClipVision/Unclip. I tested this setup with thousands of image generations to fine tune the optimal settings and give good results out of the box. 

4MOOF is a 4-image-input SMOOSH with per image pre-processing color correction as well as a universal mask between all 4.  

This tool is great for throwing 4 random images and seeing what comes out because you don't need a text prompt. It does better without one. But it's also great for putting 4 SIMILAR images and getting a wild combination/interpretation of their combined concepts, textures, colors, and feel.


****** General Notes ******

-- I've only tested the settings for THIS resolution output (1152 x 1728) at THIS aspect ratio (2:3). 

-- RESOLUTIONS - The SDXL Resolution node is a great resource for setting the size of the CLIP/CONDITIONING for the model so that it's compatible with the 1024esque training data.  
But you're not locked into that size. The Latent image size is what will become the final image size.  You can resize all 4 of your images using the Image Width and Height nodes which will determine the final output size since that is the size of the latent data being encoded by the VAE encode.

-- If you prefer to use images that don't match aspect ratio, this will stretch them in ways you won't like, so you may need to customize the "image resize" nodes per image to fit those, just keep in mind: your latent will look funky if you're layering in images with different aspect ratios.

-- The interface is tweaked for PRACTICAL USE to load it up with images and mess with prompts and make images. All the non-essential nodes are moved off screen so the usable pieces can be more prominent.  If you prefer a more strung-out version with organization and obvious flow, feel free to blow it up and do that.

nodes.title: 4MOOF TWEAKABLE VARIABLES
widgets_values:
-- -- -- These two variables have the most control in 4MOOF -- -- --

-- KSampler CFG works best between 8-26.  CFG plays a HUGE role in determining the results from broad strokes at the low end to complex and detailed at higher values. I like 9.5, 13, 17, 21. Lower CFG for anything with faces, higher CFG if the results aren't picking up on the details in your images. I don't think there's a one-size-fits all for this. I think you need to tune it based on your prompts and each set of 4 images.

--KSampler Denoise works best between 0.45 and 0.7. 0.6 sweet-spot? I've had better results with higher numbers, just not with anything much below 0.5. shrug.

-- -- -- Use these variables to tweak and fine tune  -- -- --

-- COLOR CORRECT nodes / per image. They're all zeroed out at the start. Lowering the gamma raises the blacks to dark grays, raising it brings the whites down to faded gray. 
If you want to add additional pre-processing to your images, I put Image re-routers above each Color Correct so you can easily find the thread and re-link it to the machine.
"Final Image Color Correct" is for processing the final image before saving.

-- MASKS: Change the mask as you wish! the 50% gray file is in my github.
There's a lot of creativity held within this mask loader. 
This is the mask that goes between the images before they're composited together in latent space. So you can also heavily influence the structure of your results by putting something other than 50% gray in that mask loader (like I did with my qrSMOOSH workflow). You can go high contrast black and white, or a nice gray depth map gradient.
I added a switcher in the mask section so you can quickly change between using the grayscale output of the mask directly to having it process the image you load there AS a depth map, which is typically used for control nets but works great in this use-case as well. We don't need the CN checkpoint here, just the Midas image processor.  1 is gray output and 2 is depth map output.

-- UNCLIP CONDITIONING: You can set the strength of each image in the clip pipeline. Color coded. The default value is 1. This becomes really hard to control if you start messing with the values here (I have).  It's also very helpful to tweak the strength if you find that you have everything ALMOST to where you want it but just can't get it right. I think using the color correct nodes per image can affect the results more directly than lowering the strength of the image, but I also like having options.

-- CONDITIONING SELECTOR:
Set a to 0 for STANDARD / Faces
Set a to 1 for WEIRD / Abstract
Sometimes they do the reverse for some reason? Play around.
0 is set to use the Concatenate Conditioning method.
1 is set to use the Average Conditioning method.
Switch it up and see how it affects your generations.

nodes.title: 4MOOF LINKS & RESOURCES
widgets_values:
******* REQUIREMENTS TO RUN 4MOOF: *******

-- SDXL Base model from StabilityAI
https://huggingface.co/stabilityai/stable-diffusion-xl-base-1.0

-- clip_vision_g.safetensors from ComfyAnonymous
https://huggingface.co/comfyanonymous/clip_vision_g/tree/main

-- Decent GPU since a lot of this will live in your VRAM
https://newegg.com

-- ComfyUI Manager plugin from ltdrdata
https://github.com/ltdrdata/ComfyUI-Manager



******* These Custom Nodes are also required after you get the ComfyUI manager installed *******

https://github.com/Derfuu/Derfuu_ComfyUI_ModdedNodes

-- ComfyUI Post Processing Nodes
https://github.com/EllangoK/ComfyUI-post-processing-nodes

-- ComfyMath
https://github.com/evanspearman/ComfyMath

-- Comfy ControlNet Pre-processors
https://github.com/Fannovel16/comfyui_controlnet_aux

https://github.com/WASasquatch/was-node-suite-comfyui

https://github.com/ltdrdata/ComfyUI-Impact-Pack

nodes.title: Condioning_to_strength (Average) Notes
widgets_values:
To = 1

From = 0

So 0.5 is the middle
and 0.75 is more to "TO"
and 0.25 is more "FROM"

widgets_values:
Set a to 0 for STANDARD / Faces

Set a to 1 for WEIRD / Abstract

Sometimes they do the reverse for some reason? Play around.

nodes.title: Mask Switcher Notes
widgets_values:
Select 1 
to use the direct grayscale output of the mask image 

Select 2
to use the DEPTH map generated from your image

Both use the same image mask loader, this just switches the results.

When you select option 1, it'll still generate the depth map, but it won't be used unless you select option 2.
